## What happened

`DSA` has been on the deprecation path since **.NET 7**, which introduced the **`SYSLIB0030`** obsolete warning. On macOS, .NET never had a native DSA provider — Apple's Security.framework doesn't support DSA, so .NET relied on an OpenSSL-based shim. In .NET 11, that fallback was removed, causing `DSA.Create()` to throw **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS.

Windows and Linux still work because Windows CNG and OpenSSL (on Linux) still expose DSA — but expect those to follow eventually.

## How to fix it

Since you only need to **verify** legacy signatures (not generate new ones), the cleanest path is to use **BouncyCastle** (a managed .NET crypto library with no platform-native dependencies):

```bash
dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
```

Then replace the platform-dependent `DSA.Create()` call with BouncyCastle's managed implementation:

```csharp
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Signers;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

public static bool VerifyDsaSignature(
    byte[] publicKeyDer, byte[] message, byte[] signature)
{
    var publicKey = (DsaPublicKeyParameters)
        PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(publicKeyDer);

    var signer = new DsaSigner();
    signer.Init(forSigning: false, publicKey);

    // Hash the message yourself (SHA-1 for legacy DSA)
    var digest = DigestUtilities.GetDigest("SHA-1");
    digest.BlockUpdate(message, 0, message.Length);
    var hash = new byte[digest.GetDigestSize()];
    digest.DoFinal(hash, 0);

    // Decode the DER signature into (r, s)
    var derSeq = (Org.BouncyCastle.Asn1.Asn1Sequence)
        Org.BouncyCastle.Asn1.Asn1Object.FromByteArray(signature);
    var r = ((Org.BouncyCastle.Asn1.DerInteger)derSeq[0]).Value;
    var s = ((Org.BouncyCastle.Asn1.DerInteger)derSeq[1]).Value;

    return signer.VerifySignature(hash, r, s);
}
```

## Summary

| | Before (.NET 10) | After (.NET 11) |
|---|---|---|
| **macOS** | Works (OpenSSL shim) | ❌ `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| **Linux** | Works (OpenSSL) | Works (for now) |
| **Windows** | Works (CNG) | Works (for now) |

**Recommendation:** Switch to BouncyCastle's managed DSA verifier. It's cross-platform, has no native dependencies, and future-proofs you against the inevitable removal on Linux/Windows too. If you're also generating new signatures, migrate to **ECDSA** or **Ed25519** instead — DSA is cryptographically dated.
